Date: 28 Sep 2000 11:57:45 GMT
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Source: Times of India, 28 Sep 2000 11:57:45.0635 (UTC) [edited

Dengue alert in New Delhi
---------------------------
NEW DELHI: The dreaded dengue has made a comeback after 7 cases were
reported from various parts of the Capital in the last week. 2 cases of
dengue had earlier been reported in January. Dengue claimed over 420 lives
in 1996.
The MCD sounded a general alert on how to prevent the breeding of the
_Aaedes aegypti_ mosquito vector, which [transmits dengue. It has
increased the number of people from 800 to 1,300 this year [who conduct
house-to-house searches and detect mosquito breeding.
The season for dengue starts from September, after the weather becomes
favorable for the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito. The mosquito needs fresh water
for its survival. The MCD has asked people to be cautious and not to allow
water to accumulate in and around their houses. The dengue mosquito is
generally found in coolers, used tires, overhead tanks and containers which
contain fresh water. The breeding cycle of the mosquito is one week. And if
water is changed and the container is cleaned, the mosquito gets killed.
--
