Date: 26 Sep 2000 19:33:17 +0200
From: Tomas Jelinek <jelinek@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>
Source: TropNetEurop: 26 Sep 2000 21:31:57 -0400 [edited


Dengue fever in travellers to the Dominican Republic
------------------------------------------------------
BARCELONA: 2 additional reports of dengue fever in travellers from the
Dominican Republic have been notified by Joaquim Gascon. The first concerns
a 22-year old Spaniard who visiting the Dominican Republic (area of Palav√©)
for 1 month on business. He exhibited classical symptoms of Dengue at the
end of the trip. (Analytical findings: WBC: 4 500; platelets: 114 000;
lymphocytes: 6.2%; ASAT/ALAT: 24/16. Dengue serology: IgM+). The second
concerns a 24 year old Spanish woman who had visited the Dominican Republic
(Monte Plata, Aldea de Chirino) for 3 weeks as a tourist. She exhibited
classical symptoms of Dengue a few days after arrival in Spain. (Analytical
findings: WBC: 3 600; platelets: 96 000; ASAT/ALAT: 162/159. Dengue
serology: IgM +). A third [doubtful case concerns a Dominican Republic
woman who had lived in Spain since 1995. During a visit to her home country
during Aug 2000, she suffered a febrile illness and recovered after a few
days during the trip. 4 weeks after the illness she exhibited positive IgG
for Dengue (but was IgM -).
In 1999, TropMedEurop saw only 2 patients with dengue fever in total.
Together with the 3 patients that were reported 2 weeks ago, we have seen 5
patients now. It appears that the risk for dengue fever in this particular
region is currently increasing.
--
Tomas Jelinek
<jelinek@lrz.uni-muenchen.de>
