Date: 21 Sep 2000 16:01:56 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
Source: Agencia EFE, filed: 21 Sep 2000 1:14 PM EST [edited

El Salvador To Punish Failure To Fight Dengue-carrying Mosquito
-----------------------------------------------------------------
SAN SALVADOR: The Salvadoran government on Thu 21 Sep 2000 announced that
fines of 1 000 to 100 000 colons [115 to 11 467 dollars would be imposed
on those who do not cooperate in the destruction of breeding sites for the
mosquitoes that transmit dengue, which has killed 28 children and 2 women
so far this year.
In a communique published in the local press, the Health Ministry said it
would enforce provisions in the health code that permit the issuance of
recommendations and imposition of sanctions on people or companies that do
not cooperate in resolving the problem. In addition, the ministry warned
that all companies and national or foreign institutions "are obligated to
participate in mosquito control projects on their property or
installations," and that all the country's residents should cooperate with
the Health Ministry in this effort.
The Salvadoran government declared a national emergency 12 Sep 2000 because
of the dengue epidemic, and has launched a media campaign to encourage the
public to destroy places where the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which
transmits dengue, might breed.
Despite these efforts, Benjamin Bloom Hospital in San Salvador, the only
hospital in the country that specializes in pediatrics, is filled with
dengue patients, and 2 more children have died of dengue this week.
According to a Health Ministry official, cases of classic dengue have
increased to nearly 2 000 so far this year and cases of hemorrhagic dengue,
the deadly variety, rose to nearly 300 in the same period.
